segments.text: Testing, testing, one, two, three, four, one, two, three, four.
One, two, three, four, testing, one, two, three, four.
This is the 3rd of April.
We're in the Cushing Library, room 207, and I have the pleasure and honor of talking to Professor Leonard Ponder.
To introduce yourself to a reader or a listener, give us a biographical summary of
Family background, growing up, what did mom and dad do?
Where high school, where college?
What did you do before coming to A&M?
I grew up in northwest Louisiana, a little town called Pleasant Hill.
Pleasant Hill is about 60 miles south of Shreveport.
Some people know where Shreveport is at least.
A little village of about 1,000 people.
My dad was a carpenter.
I was the baby of five boys.
My youngest brother is seven years older than me, which means I was an accident and fully expected to be a girl.
In fact, my mother quilted a pink quilt for me, but alas, tomorrow, it didn't work out that way.
Pleasant Hill High School has fond memories for that place.
I was fortunate enough to play basketball there.
I was not a great athlete, but
Because it was a small school, nearly everyone could play.
We started in September and finished in March.
We'd play 50 or 60 games a year.
So if you do that for five or six years, counting junior high, you get to where you can play a little.
That probably kept me in school and interested in school until I got old enough to realize that that was an important thing.
Because in my family, my mother went to the
Eighth grade, my dad finished the sixth grade.
Of course, that's all the school there was where they were at the time.
My mother was a teacher for a while.
She passed the Louisiana teacher's test and was able to teach for a year or two.
So I had a role model from that point of view.
From there, I went to Northwestern State University in Natchitoches, which was about 45 minutes from where I grew up.
At that time, Northwestern had 2,500 students.
And I thought, surely I had died in going to New York City because I'd never seen so many people in one place.
After graduating there, I went to Shreveport and taught in a brand new school, Oak Terrace Junior High.
What?
Oak Terrace Junior High.
Oak Terrace, okay.
And Sunset Acres, which is the western part of, and Blue Collar part of the town.
I was a teacher and a coach.
I coached football, basketball, and track.
I played basketball and never played a down of football.
I was very poor.
My one loss record in basketball was very poor.
I had a very good one loss record in football, probably because I didn't try to over-encompass the youngsters.
But a bigger reason was because I had a couple of players that were pretty good.
A guy named Terry Bradshaw was one of our quarterbacks.
and he was followed up by a fellow named Joe Ferguson.
And of course Haskell knows that Bradshaw played for the Pittsburgh Steelers and Ferguson played for the Buffalo Bills after playing for Arkansas.
So they made me better than I was.
Were you the head coach?
I was head coach.
And what was the one loss record when they were there?
Well, when they were there,
When Bradshaw was there, we were like five and three.
We played eight games a year.
Ferguson had a better year.
By then, we had our program going.
And I honestly don't remember the record, but it was 7-1, 6-2, something like that.
But the interesting thing was neither of those kids threw the ball much because we didn't have anyone to catch it.
But they were leaders at that time, and we knew they were going to be good high school players.
We didn't know whether they'd be good
get college and pros.
From there, I went to Southeastern Louisiana University and taught for four or five years.
I didn't have my doctorate yet.
You had done your master's where?
I had finished my master's at Northwestern also.
While I was teaching in Shreveport, I went back to Northwestern and finished my master's.
While at Southeastern, it became very apparent that if I was going to stay in higher education, I needed the doctorate, so
I took a leave of absence and went to the University of Tennessee and got my degree there.
From Tennessee I went back to Southeastern for a year and then came over here.
What year?
I came with the whole slug of everyone else who came in 1972.
How did you and A&M get linked together?
Yeah.
Like how did you know there was a vacancy and how did they know you existed?
I went to our national meeting.
In our field, the national organization was the American Association for Health, Physical Education, Recreation, and Dance.
And some would say possible safety.
It was a long, lengthy thing.
But they had their national meeting in Houston.
And I went to that meeting.
And they have a very fine placement center.
And I went there and looked through all the job opportunities.
And of course, A&M was listed.
They also had an employee section where you could list your credentials.
So I left my credentials.
And I didn't interview there, nor did I apply for the job.
But I went back to Southeastern.
And a couple weeks, Carl Landis, who was the department head, called me and asked me if I'd come for an interview.
And had you met him?
I had never met him.
I saw him at the convention.
Someone pointed him out to me.
But I had not met him.
I knew no one at A&M.
Fortunately, the job that I was applying for, they were interested in me for, was to direct allied health education, which was a brand new thing, a brand new thing nationally and new on this campus.
Baylor College of Medicine had gotten a grant to prepare teachers of allied health so that they would then in turn take faculty jobs and prepare other allied health professionals.
And there just wasn't many applicants because no one knew anything about it.
And I didn't either, to tell you the truth.
But Carl convinced me that it was a good opportunity.
And of course, I was impressed with A&M the minute I walked on campus.
All right.
And so you drove over.
I drove over.
And describe the entire visit, particularly the interview process.
I want to start back a little further than that.
Oh, okay.
All right, good.
My wife and I had been married then seven, I see six, about eight years.
No, ten years, near ten years.
Had never had a vacation.
So that particular summer, we decided we would, and we had a new baby.
We took baby to grandparents, and we went down to the Gulf Coast of Mississippi.
And I lay on the beach and took in the sun and got so sunburned we had to stand up.
We couldn't even sleep.
I couldn't lay down to sleep.
And we had just come in and the phone was ringing as we walked in the door and it was Carl Landis.
And he asked me if I would be at A&M the next day.
Oh, my.
And I says, Dr. Landis, I just got here.
I just don't think I can do that.
And he said, well, I'm trying to get away on vacation.
It sure would be nice.
Maybe you could come partway.
And so I told him that we'd get in.
This is like 3 o'clock in the afternoon.
So I told him we'd go in as far as we could.
And, in fact, we got to Beaumont that night.
And then the next day drove on in.
And I can recall driving through Navasota.
And we didn't go through Hempstead.
We came in off of 105.
And it was desolate, as you remember back then.
There wasn't much back there.
And of course, Highway 6 ran right through the heart of Navasota.
We topped a hill, and there sat A&M, like an oasis.
There was nothing, and then there was a lot.
And we found G. Ryder White very easily.
And I had my wife with me, and we met with Carl and had a good visit.
Of course, Carl Landis, as you recall, was very straight and dignified and very formal in all he did.
I don't recall all of the interview, but I do recall the interview with Frank Hubert, who was then dean of education.
Describe that one.
We went into his office and it was his birthday.
And the secretaries had baked a cake and he had the cake container on his desk and it was empty.
We came in and of course he did his customary Frank Hubert thing with his hands together.
And he began to ask me questions.
And when we got through talking, and my wife was with me again, and my wife has never been known to be quiet.
She would not, that just wasn't her.
She actually was an introvert, but she was very extroverted in her behavior.
And the two of them carried on a nice conversation as well.
But as we finished, he asked me if I had any questions.
And I said that I did, that I'd like to know what the load expectation was, what the teaching load was.
No, I'm sorry.
I want to know what the research responsibility was.
Because 1972, if you recall, was just about the time when that pendulum started swinging.
And he said that it was a considerable research responsibility.
And then he kind of looked at me out of the corner of his eye and said, do you have a problem with that?
And I told him that I wasn't sure that I did, depending on what the teaching load was.
And he said, well, it's 12 hours.
And I'd been carrying 15.
And 12 hours sounded pretty good.
When we finished, I don't guess I made a very good impression on him.
Or maybe I asked some of the wrong questions.
Because years later, Carl Landis
told me that when we walked out, Hubert looked at him and said, you don't want ponder, do you?
And Carl said, yes, I do.
And Carl told me that in the spirit that it wasn't long before that Frank Hubert had named me department head.
And apparently I made the team somewhere along the way.
Go back to what do you recall about the interview process with Carl Landis?

interesting thing about that he had just he'd had a guy named charles corbin and that name might need to be erased in the final draft you may know it may remember him chuck was a very good teacher and and the students really related to him very well but he was kind of a an outlaw in on the faculty he didn't have much respect for any authority and
Now, I wasn't here then, but I heard all the stories.
And Carl had been burned by him pretty badly.
And rules were not for Charles.
And so in looking back at the interview, I understand it better now than I did then.
But he asked me a lot of questions about how I felt about
a faculty member's role and an administrator's role and those kinds of things.
But the thing that really disturbed me the most was that the first year I felt kind of shut out.
I felt he was really cold to me.
From my perspective, I'd worked in a university where a new faculty came in and they were kind of given the exalted seat for a while and a lot of attention and welcoming.
I never felt that the whole time I was there.
Later I discovered that Carl wanted to be sure that he never got behind the eight ball with another faculty member.
And he was a little concerned about that.
Did you get from this first visit, this interview visit, did you get any perception of what the guidelines, the rules, the expectations were for a new faculty member?
I think so.
Not to the extent that probably I would have liked to.
I knew from the interview that you were going to work from 8 to 5.
You were going to be in your office from 8 to 5, probably.
No one was going to go up and down checking on you, but that was the expectation.
I also learned, much to my dismay, that when the students were gone, that doesn't necessarily mean the faculty were gone.
That was not modeled anywhere in the country, I suppose.
They made very clear to me what the teaching load was and what the expectations in the classroom were, and they didn't equivocate about that.
That was laid out pretty closely.
The thing that impressed me more than anything and probably removed all doubt was before I left that day, he made me an offer.
and told me what the money was.
This is the only dollar question all day.
All day, that's right.
What was the opening salary, the beginning salary?
Opening salary was 17,000.
For 12 or nine?
For 12 months.
For 12 months.
Now he made me the offer and made me the sour quote.
I didn't expect either of those.
And instead I had to say I need to think about it.
Someone, a wise person told me one time never take a job during an interview because you'll take every job you interview for that way.
And so when I went back home we thought about it and decided to take the job.
And then when he made the offer, when he actually sent me the letter, he had upped it $500.
So he quoted me $17,000, paid me $17,500, and I've never forgotten that.
And that added to the plus.
Oh, no question.
And I used that a few times when I was department head.
If I could e-cap another $200 or $300 for someone we were interviewing, I always dumped it in because it's a nice message to send.
Make believe that I didn't know Carl Landis.
Describe him.
in your first impressions and then later.
Okay.
Very dignified, very matter of fact and to the point, doesn't waste words, economy of words.
very high morals, expects people around him to behave that way.
A gentleman in every respect.
A military man.
He was in the military, but later I don't call him, I wouldn't consider him a military person, but he behaved like a military person.
As I got to know him,
And this was years later.
I discovered that he was pretty much a pussycat, very soft-hearted, a kind man, a little bit unsure of himself.
And probably that's why he was so formal.
Formality gave him some structure that he liked.
Now, did you call any friends or anything to find out information about him?
Actually, I talked to my major professor at Tennessee.
He was the only person I talked to.
What did they say?
What did he say?
He said that he thought it was a good school, but don't forget, Leonard, it's a military school.
I remember this is 1972 and the military was out of favor at that point.
He said that your degree is health education, your discipline is health education, and I don't really believe they're committed to health education at A&M.
I think they have health just because it may look good.
Now, that was an indictment on the department, not on the university.
But the good thing about it is I knew a lot about A&M because being in a general proximity of the state, I watched them come over and play LSU football
And I was always in the Army with an Aggie who, in fact, I served under an Aggie who I thought was one of the best commanders I ever had.
So I knew a lot already about them.
Then my undergraduate alma mater, the guy who was department head at my undergraduate university was a classmate of mine, a former classmate.
And he knew a lot about A&M.
And I really depended on him more than anyone else.
Did you hear any, other than the possibility of the emphasis on military, did you hear any other negatives about A&M as you were trying to check up and learn things?
I don't think I heard anything negative.
And I probably didn't explore it as deep as someone who didn't know much about the university would have.
And this is the fall of 72.
One of the ironies is that Jack Williams, the comparatively new president,
had just been the chief academic officer of the University of Tennessee system.
That's right, and I knew that.
Before coming.
I knew that, but I wouldn't have called him.
No way I would have called him.
I understand.
I was a student.
When he was at Tennessee, I was a student.
In fact, he left there while I was a student.
Now, the name of the official title of the department when you arrived was what?
Health and Physical Education.
And it offered, in general, what did the department in those days offer when you arrived?
It had one undergraduate degree, and it was health and physical education.
People who went through that primarily were prepared to be teachers.
And it was primarily to teach physical education.
There was also, I counted there were 11 health courses offered, but only six hours in the curriculum at that time.
We had no degree in health, but a number of people would take those courses, some of the elective courses, to beef up their health background.
Supposedly, they were certified to teach both health and physical education, but they were really qualified to teach physical education.
At the graduate level, we had also a degree in health and physical education, and the doctoral level was just health and physical education.
And the doctoral degree was already at that time?
It was already at that time.
It was brand new.
I think they were in their third year.
Was it an Ed.D.
or a Ph.D. or both?
It was both.
It was both.
And do you have any guesstimate when you got here what the enrollment was in number of majors?
As a matter of fact, I do.
I brought some cheats.
I know I wrote that number down.
Well, in 1979, we had 160 health majors, 535 physical education.
So that's 685, isn't it?
And that was twice as many as we had in 1972.
So it's half 685, whatever that is.
I can't do that.
And were there many graduate students when you arrived?
Not many.
They'd had a brand new doctoral program.
Their first class had just about graduated.
A few strikers from the first class left.
And there was about six or eight of those fellows out there.
All of them were men.
The only woman PhD student at that time was Gail Smith.
You know Norma Gail, I think.
S-C-H-M-I-D-T?
S-C-H-M-I-D-T, yeah.
All right, now...
This offer came at about what time on the calendar?
This was late July.
And they needed you here when?
Mid-August.
So describe what the routine was for you and wife and young child to get over here.
Well, we had just built a house.
We'd been in it two years, I guess.
We built it and then took a leave of absence, went to Tennessee.
So we'd only lived in it about two years.
We had to sell that house.
And that was, of course, a scramble.
But fortunately, I never had to put it on the market.
There was someone in the neighborhood who wanted to buy it.
I actually came earlier than they wanted me to.
I finished my duties at Southeastern in about mid-July.
Maybe it was later than that.
Maybe it was toward the end of July.
And I had no other responsibilities to the university after that.
So I packed my bags and came to A&M.
I got here sooner than Carl expected me to.
And I remember going up two or three.
And I didn't realize they were still in summer session.
I thought they were out of summer session, too.
And I'd come up and look for my office.
Well, it's not ready yet.
And two or three days, I would do that.
We were getting real crowded over there then, and so I discovered after I got here I was going to have to share an office with someone else.
What was it like to move?
Did you move yourself or a commercial?
No, someone moved me.
I hired a Mayflower company to move in.
Of course, no help from A&M.
Describe what the housing opportunities were here.
What did you find?
Actually, it turned out pretty good.
We came over here and met with a realtor who happened to be Robert Smith's brother.
It was Robert's wife.
I'm forgetting her name for some reason.
I don't know why.
Richard was just getting his operation going good.
She showed us around the neighborhood and it was very good.
There were several houses open at that time.
But, you know, $40,000.
And I paid like 18 for mine.
And there was just no way I could swing that.
But what I didn't know, being as young as I was, is when I sold my house, I sold it for 35.
So I could have done that.
But we really wanted to rent.
And we made that known very early.
And much to my surprise, she worked with us on that and found us a rent house, which was good marketing on her part.
Because later on, when I got ready to buy a house, I went straight to her and asked her to have the deal.
Do you remember what that rent was?
Gosh, it was about 150.
In College Station or in Bryan?
It was in Bryan.
It was in Bryan.
I wanted to get out of College Station because I wanted to get out and know some of the people that were not university people.
Same here.
And I don't know if what happened to you happened to me, but what happened to me happened to you.
But when I finally built a house, or bought a house, it was over on Memorial Drive near St. Joseph.
And nearly everybody over there worked for the university anyway.
But we've enjoyed Brian, I'm not sorry I did that.
Alright, so as you first went to the office, describe the facilities and the offices and so forth for the entire department.
They're not good facilities at all.
We were in a new building where I'd come from and I was a little disappointed to find that I had to be partnered with someone and share an office.
Turned out to be a good thing because that was a guy named Robert Hurley who was at that time chair of the health education program.
And we got to be good friends because we were able to work together.
Classrooms, the chairs were nailed down, military listed seats, noisy.
And I had visions I was going to change all that.
I was going to bring the light of day to this place.
That's obviously what I discovered very quickly.
I wasn't going to do that.
They were satisfied with where they'd done things.
And where was this?
This was all in G. Riley White, which was an old building then, of course.
Well, it was built in the 50s, and this was 72.
But I also learned...
Everything negative I heard about A&M I heard after I got here.
And there were things that I didn't think was all that negative.
One of the first things I heard was General Rutter's famous statement about Highway 6 goes both ways.
And to be honest with you, I kind of like that.
At first, what did you think that really meant, implied?
Well, it was told to me in a context that it was tainted by the way this person interpreted it to me.
But he was being very critical of Rutter.
He had come from University of Illinois and couldn't understand why A&M couldn't be more like Illinois.
And he interpreted and expressed it to me as though you don't dare speak up around here.
You say it the way we want to hear it and otherwise leave it alone.
And that may have been the way it was said.
I didn't serve under General Rutter.
He had died the year before I got here and Jack Williams was
was president.
And I really liked him.
There's been a lot of good presidents since I've been here, but he was really, really fun to go to a faculty meeting when he was in China.
Let's go ahead and talk about him.
Make believe I didn't know him and describe him.
I'll never forget the first time I met him was at the new faculty dinner.
Were those not great occasions?
I don't know if they still do that or not, but boy, that was really a neat day.
I hear they don't.
That's too bad, because my wife and I were invited, of course, and we didn't know anyone except just a few people we'd met in the department.
And we all filed in, and I saw that spread, and I could not believe what they had done.
Now, keep in mind that what I was experiencing in the department was kind of a cold shoulder, you know, we're not going to,
Now, I was introduced last in the faculty meeting, for example.
I fully walked in expecting to be the first one introduced because I was new.
Well, that wasn't what happened.
Well, here was, that had been turned around 180 degrees.
I mean, they're treating you like you're the most special person ever.
Jack Williams addressed us after dinner, and I have never laughed so hard in my life.
I don't remember everything he said, but I know a couple of stories that he told.
One was,
He said that some of you know that I've only been president here for just about a year.
He said, when I first got here, I got a letter from a guy.
You've heard the story about him.
Please go ahead.
I got a letter from the guy who said, Dr. Williams, when I first heard that you were going to be president and you weren't even an Aggie, I didn't like it very much.
But since I've been reading about you and Aggie, I think you might do.
But I want you to know I'm watching you damn close.
And he'd tell that and just beam as he said it.
And then another story he told was he said, you know, in administration, friends come and friends go, but enemies accumulate.
And I've carried that with me a long, long time.
But the whole evening was just really good.
All right.
And the result of that evening in your feelings was what?
What did you and your wife think when you drove?
Very, very positive.
Very positive.
There was no...
I was beginning to wonder if I had made the right move.
But that evening turned that thinking around almost entirely.
But you asked me about Jack Williams.
I was being a new assistant professor.
I didn't have a lot of interaction with him.
Nearly all the interaction I had was formal.
But he had a delightful sense of humor.
a great speaking voice, put you at ease, or at least I felt he put you at ease very quickly.
I found out later that he also was a tough nut to crack.
You had to have your duck lined up to get through that gentleman.
It really was
It really was too bad that his health turned the way it did, because he had this university movement in leaps and bounds.
Let me add in, this is an editorial note.
I was at that point a new administrator.
My title was Assistant Vice President for Academic Affairs.
And as we were looking forward that fall to planning the faculty orientation,
One day I went in Dr. Williams' office and he told me to take charge of that.
And I began to tell him how poorly it had been done in the past.
And so he said, if you know so much about how it ought to be done, you plan it.
So what we tried to do was to have a day of a bit of a tour of the campus for new faculty and spouses and to encourage as many of them to come as possible.
and to take them to a few of the places where the average faculty member wouldn't ever get to go.
Then that evening, to have a formal dinner, everyone dress up, department heads, new faculty, deans, and so forth, and then have Dr. Williams make one of those speeches that he could do so well.
And then I think I said on that first one, I know I did in the later ones,
And conclusion, ladies and gentlemen, this evening will be a success if, when you are driving home this evening, one of you looks at the other and says, honey, I'm kind of glad we're here.
Our hope was to get everybody off to a positive start and to begin to build a feeling of community, of working together.
And Dr. Williams was so encouraging in that regard that it made it an effort of joy.
